# **1\. Introduction** {#1.-introduction}

## **1.1 Purpose** {#1.1-purpose}

The software design document (SDD) is a collection of models used to illustrate data design, architectural design, interface design, and procedural design. This document should be referenced by Pioneers of Software (PiOS) as an outline of GUIs and requirement execution in terms of design. This document will also be reviewed by the stakeholder/client to manage expectations of what will and will not be implemented in the final product, and to allow feedback of any misunderstandings that may have formed during this process.

There are four aspects of design that go into this design document: data design, architectural design, interface design, and procedural design.

The data design outlines all class objects to be used when designing the software.

The architecture design will expand upon those relationships by graphing hierarchical functions in a general flowchart. 

The interface design provides a visual representation of internal, external, and user interfaces.

The procedural design uses diagrams to illustrate the process for functions of PiPa.

## **1.2 Scope** {#1.2-scope}

The SDD will relate most closely to the actual development of the software. The final product should follow and reflect the finalized version of this document.

It will not elaborate on tests, communication of customer expectations, or contain any complete iterations of the software.

The SDD contains the following sections:

* Data Design  
* Architecture Design  
* Interface Design  
* Procedural Design

## **1.5 System Overview** {#1.5-system-overview}

The PiPa software will be designed as a POS system for the client, \[Names\], according to his needs for his business. The main functionality of this software is to take orders using a GUI focused software that calculates price and displays a receipt. The software will function using a Windows computer with a mouse and keyboard by several users with a log-in system.

---

# **2\. Data Design** {#2.-data-design}

This section outlines all data structures to be implemented and how they should be implemented.

## **2.1 Internal Data Structures** {#2.1-internal-data-structures}

### **2.1.1 User Database** {#2.1.1-user-database}

The user database must be mutable and thus, should not be hardcoded; the user database, therefore, will be saved on a .csv file as Strings, and the software will write and read Strings to and from this .csv file.

### **2.1.2 Price Database** {#2.1.2-price-database}

The price database must be mutable and thus, should not be hardcoded; the price database, therefore, will be written to and read from a .csv file as String entries. Within our software, we will extract the Strings of the .csv file, and cast them to double values so that they can be mathematically applied to our software processes.

### **2.1.3 Miscellaneous Data** {#2.1.3-miscellaneous-data}

Passive data such as: \[pizza toppings, pizza sizes, time and date\] must be hardcoded into the program as the user should not be able to change these variables.

## **2.2 Data Flow Diagram** {#2.2-data-flow-diagram}

Data flow diagrams describe the relationship between hardware and software devices, and the information each can communicate to each other. 

The Level 0 diagram communicates this with the POS system being highly abstracted, only focusing on the information exchanged.

![][image2]

The Level 1 diagram is slightly less abstract in its visualization of the POS system. It expresses what information is communicated between each function of the software, without communicating how these functions will actually behave in depth.![][image3]

## **2.3 Data Dictionary** {#2.3-data-dictionary}

The data dictionary will be used as a guide by PiOS team members \[Names\]and \[Names\] to recall the necessary aspects of the software. Attribute names are descriptive, and may not currently reflect what they will be called in the program. 

| Attribute Name | Required | Format | Max Field Size | Notes |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| User ID | Yes | String | 24 | The name of the user. |
| User PIN | Yes | String | 4 | A password per User |
| Item | Yes | String | 128 | Pizza, Soda, Etc. |
| Quantity | Yes | Integer | 4 | Of item |
| Toppings | Yes | Tuple/ ENUM List | 9 | Toppings are hard coded in program |
| Sizes | Yes | Tuple/ ENUM List | 3 | There are three sizes |
| Prices \[items\] | Yes | Array \[Double\] | 7 | Of items, as set by user |
| Prices \[totals\] | No | Array \[Double\] | 128 | Of totals, for bookkeeping |
| Price (tax) | Yes | Double | 3 | Taxes should not exceed \-2nd decimal place |
| Time and Date | Yes | String | 16 | For receipt, (‘/’,‘ ‘& ‘:’ counted) |

# **4\. Interface Design** {#4.-interface-design}

The interface designs contain internal, external, and user interfaces. These are designed to expand upon the architecture model and to further depict visual and operational interfaces.

## **4.1 Internal System Interfaces** {#4.1-internal-system-interfaces}

Data largely exists in the program to serve the needs of the receipt; different aspects of the software should interface directly with the receipt aspect. Ordering and placing order can be considered a pre-step of gathering receipt data.  
Internal models follow entity relation graphing standards.

#### 	**4.1.1 Receipt Interface** {#4.1.1-receipt-interface}

		Modalities:

* The Receipt Field needs the Inherent field, but the Inherent Field doesn’t need the Receipt Field  
* The Receipt Field needs the Price Field, but the Price Field doesn’t need the Receipt Field  
* The Receipt Field needs the Users Field, but the Users Field doesn’t need the Receipt Field  
* The Receipt Field needs the Tax Field, but the Tax Field doesn’t need the Receipt Field

  Cardinalities: 

* There needs to only be one occurring date/ time for each receipt.   
* There needs to only only be one user for each receipt; there needs to only be one name to each PIN.  
* There can be many order items and pizza items to each receipt.  
* Order prices need to remain consistent through the receipt; there can only be one set of order prices throughout the receipt.  
* There can be multiple order prices.  
* Tax prices need to remain consistent through the receipt.


  

## **4.2 External System Interfaces** {#4.2-external-system-interfaces}

The PiPa POS software will be self contained in a single stand-alone program, and therefore has no external interfaces.

# **5\. Procedural Design** {#5.-procedural-design}

Our team has constructed several flowcharts to facilitate programmer and customer understanding of the usage of the program. Processing flow is depicted for all requirement functions.

## **5.1 Flowchart Reference Key** {#5.1-flowchart-reference-key}

### **5.1.1 Initiators and Terminators** {#5.1.1-initiators-and-terminators}

		Green ovals represent program starts, red ovals are program terminators.  
![][image13]![][image14]

### **5.1.2 Process** {#5.1.2-process}

The process is represented by a white rectangle; it explains an action the program will complete  
![][image15]

### **5.1.3 Predefined Process** {#5.1.3-predefined-process}

The predefined process is represented by a white rectangle with two subrectangles; it contains a process set, and a reference flowchart where that set is drawn out.  
They will contain a brief description, and a ‘Go:’ to guide readers to which flowchart the predefined process refers to.  
	  
![][image16]

### **5.1.4 Decisions** {#5.1.4-decisions}

Decisions are represented by a blue diamond. They indicate where the user must input a choice in the software.  
![][image17]

### **5.1.5 Directional Symbols** {#5.1.5-directional-symbols}

Arrows and bubbles represent the flow between the software processes. They show direction and assist in reading the flowchart.  
![][image18]

### **5.1.6 Local Data Storage** {#5.1.6-local-data-storage}

Local Data Storage is that which is temporarily stored, and stored locally. The program will create this data per-instance.  
It is represented by a purple rectangle, with a cross section in its top left.

### **![][image19]**

### **5.1.7 General Data Storage** {#5.1.7-general-data-storage}

General Data Storage is that which is stored across sessions. The program will either set new data, or get current data.  
It is represented by a purple rectangle, with rounded sides.  
![][image20]
